ratextual Ovid -- tIntratextual Readings in Ovid’s Heroides -- tIntrepid Intratextuality: The Epistolary Pair of Leander and Hero (Heroides 18–19) and the End of Ovid’s Poetic Career -- tSome Polyvalent Intra- and Inter-Textualities in Fasti 3 -- tOvid, ex Ponto 4: An Intratextually Cohesive Book -- tPart VI: Seneca: Prose and Poetry -- tNulla res est quae non eius quo nascitur notas reddat (Nat. 3.21.2): Intertext to Intratext in Senecan Prose and Poetry -- tIntertextuality and Intratextuality: Euripides’ Iphigenia at Aulis and Seneca’s Troades -- tPart VII: Neronian and Flavian Intratextual Poetics -- tPraise and Flattery in the Latin Epic: A Case of Intratextuality -- tLucan’s Intra/Inter-textual Poetics: Deconstructing Caesar in Lucan -- tIntratextuality via Philosophy: Contextualizing ira in Silius Italicus’ Punica 1‒2 -- tInside Epigram: Intratextuality in Martial’s Epigrams, Book 10 -- tPart VIII: Roman Prose and Encyclopedic Literature -- t‘Political Intratextuality’ with regard to Cicero’s Speeches -- tOn the Economy of ‘Sending and Receiving Information’ in Roman Historiography -- tSaturnalian Riddles for Attic Nights: Intratextual Feasting with Aulus Gellius -- tPart IX: Rounding off Intratextuality: Greece and Rome -- tRegius urget: Hellenising Thoughts on Latin Intratextuality -- tList of Contributors -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent years have witnessed an increased interest in classical studies in the ways meaning is generated through the medium of intertextuality, namely how different texts of the same or different authors communicate and interact with each other. Attention (although on a lesser scale) has also been paid to the manner in which meaning is produced through interaction between various parts of the same text or body of texts within the overall production of a single author, namely intratextuality. Taking off from the seminal volume on Intratextuality: Greek and Roman Textual Relations, edited by A. Sharrock / H. Morales (Oxford 2000), which largely sets the theoretical framework for such internal associations within classical texts, this collective volume brings together twenty-seven contributions, written by an international team of experts, exploring the evolution of intratextuality from Late Republic to Late Antiquity across a wide range of authors, genres and historical periods. Of particular interest are also the combined instances of intra- and intertextual poetics as well as the way in which intratextuality in Latin literature draws on reading practices and critical methods already theorized and operative in Greek antiquity.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aIntratextualität. 4aLateinische Literatur. 4aLiteraturtheorie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aLatin Literature.  aintertextuality.  aintratextuality.1 aAntoniadis, Theodore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgelhaaf-Gaiser, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabre-Serris, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrangoulidis, Stavros, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrangoulidis, Stavros, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFranklinos, Tristan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuhrer, Therese, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFulkerson, Laurel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardie, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Stephen J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/voc